own]]\n* [[Tallanstown]]\n* [[Termonfeckin]]\n* [[Tinure]]\n* [[Tullyallen, County Louth|Tullyallen]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Local government and politics==\n\n===Louth County Council===\n{{Main|Louth County Council}}\nThe local authority is Louth County Council, offices in Dundalk, which provides a number of services including planning, roads maintenance, fire brigade, council housing, water supply, waste collection, recycling and landfill, higher education grants and funding for arts and culture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Services/ |title=Services |publisher=Louth County Council |accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the implementation of the [[Local Government Reform Act 2014]] on 1 June 2014, County Louth has been subdivided into four Local Electoral Areas (often abbreviated as LEA) for elections to [[Louth County Council]] and three [[Municipal district (Ireland)|Municipal districts]] for local government, which are:\n<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[File:County Louth local electoral areas.jpg|thumb|right|Local electoral ares in County Louth]] -->\n* Ardee Municipal District\n* Drogheda Borough District\n* [[Dundalk Municipal District]]\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Council \n! Area \n! District<br><ref group=\"t\">Y indicates the area is a municipal district. (Those designated as \"metropolitan district\" or \"borough district\" are footnoted.)</ref> \n! LEA<br><ref group=\"t\">Y indicates the area is a local electoral area.</ref> \n! Councillors<br><ref group=\"t\">The number of Councillors returned by the LEA and/or the number on the district council. All district councillors are ''ex officio'' members of the county/city council.</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=5|[[Louth County Council]] (29) || [[Ardee]] || Y || Y || 6\n|-\n| [[Drogheda]] || Y<ref group=\"t\" name=\"borough\">Borough district.</ref> || Y || 10\n|-\n| [[Dundalk]] || Y || || 13\n|-\n| Dundalk [[Carlingford, County Louth|Carlingford]] || || Y || 6\n|-\n| Dundalk South || || Y || 7\n|-\n|}\nKey:\n{{reflist|group=t}}\n\n===Louth D\u00e1il constituency===\n{{Main|Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)}}\nFor elections to D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann, Louth is represented by the five member [[Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)|Louth constituency]] which takes in the entire county of Louth and two electoral divisions in [[County Meath]]. \nthe [[Electoral (Amendment) Act 2009]] merged the electoral divisions of St.Mary's (Part) and Julianstown, collectively known as \"[[East Meath]]\" in [[County Meath]] with County Louth to form one Louth D\u00e1il constituency.\n\nThe Report on D\u00e1il and European Parliament Constituencies 2007 outlined;<blockquote>''\"by extending the constituency southwards from, and in the environs of, Drogheda and taking in electoral divisions which have extensive linkages with the town. This will allow the inclusion of the town of Drogheda and hinterland areas in a single constituency.\"''<ref>http://www.constituency-commission.ie/docs%5Ccon2007.pdfThis{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> </blockquote>This merger allowed the areas of the Greater Drogheda area in [[County Meath]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.droghedaboro.ie/droghedaboro/downloads/Drogheda%20Issues%20paper.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812081706/http://www.droghedaboro.ie/droghedaboro/downloads/Drogheda%20Issues%20paper.pdf |archivedate=12 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and their combined population of 20,375 to be merged with [[Drogheda]] and County Louth.\n\nFollowing the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]], the constituency elected two TDs for the [[Fine Gael]] party (centre right), and one touchdown each for [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] (centre to centre-right), the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] (centre left) and [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] (left wing).\n\n==Irish language==\nThe area of Omeath was Irish-speaking until the early 20th century. A native dialect of Louth Irish existed there until about 1930 but is now extinct, although recordings have been made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doegen.ie/taxonomy/term/21984|title=The Doegen Records Web Project|date=2009|website=Doegen|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref>\n\n34.07% of the population of County Louth are Irish speakers, with 790 people who use Irish on a daily basis and 2,276 people who use Irish on a weekly basis outside the education system, according to the 2016 census.<ref name=cso2016/>\n\n==People==\n\n===Entertainment===\n*[[Pierce Brosnan]] - Actor, [[James Bond]]\n*[[Eamonn Campbell]] - Member of [[The Dubliners]]\n*[[Andrea Corr]] - Singer, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Caroline Corr]] - Musician, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Jim Corr]] - Musician, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Sharon Corr]] - Musician, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Evanna Lynch]] -  Actress, ''[[Harry Potter]]''\n*[[Cathy Maguire]] - Singer/songwriter\n*[[John Moore (director)|John Moore]] - Film director\n*[[Gerry O'Connor (fiddle player)|Gerry O'Connor]] - Traditional [[Irish fiddle playing|Irish fiddle]] player\n*[[Colin O'Donoghue]] - Actor, ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''\n\n===Military===\n*[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Francis Leopold McClintock]] [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] - [[Royal Navy]] officer and [[Explorer]]\n*[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General]] [[Arthur Thomas Moore]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]] - Soldier and recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]]\n*[[James Sheridan (Medal of Honor)]] , [[Quartermaster]] [[United States]] during the [[American Civil War]] - Sailor and recipient of the [[Medal of Honor]] for action at [[Battle of Mobile Bay]]\n\n===Politics===\n*[[Dermot Ahern]] - Politician, [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] for Louth\n*[[James Carroll (Louth politician)|James Carroll]] - Politician, [[Fianna F\u00e1il]], member of [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]] from Louth\n*[[Mark Dearey]] -