uthority is Louth County Council, offices in Dundalk, which provides a number of services including planning, roads maintenance, fire brigade, council housing, water supply, waste collection, recycling and landfill, higher education grants and funding for arts and culture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.louthcoco.ie/en/Services/ |title=Services |publisher=Louth County Council |accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the implementation of the [[Local Government Reform Act 2014]] on 1 June 2014, County Louth has been subdivided into four Local Electoral Areas (often abbreviated as LEA) for elections to [[Louth County Council]] and three [[Municipal district (Ireland)|Municipal districts]] for local government, which are:\n<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[File:County Louth local electoral areas.jpg|thumb|right|Local electoral ares in County Louth]] -->\n* Ardee Municipal District\n* Drogheda Borough District\n* [[Dundalk Municipal District]]\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Council \n! Area \n! District<br><ref group=\"t\">Y indicates the area is a municipal district. (Those designated as \"metropolitan district\" or \"borough district\" are footnoted.)</ref> \n! LEA<br><ref group=\"t\">Y indicates the area is a local electoral area.</ref> \n! Councillors<br><ref group=\"t\">The number of Councillors returned by the LEA and/or the number on the district council. All district councillors are ''ex officio'' members of the county/city council.</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=5|[[Louth County Council]] (29) || [[Ardee]] || Y || Y || 6\n|-\n| [[Drogheda]] || Y<ref group=\"t\" name=\"borough\">Borough district.</ref> || Y || 10\n|-\n| [[Dundalk]] || Y || || 13\n|-\n| Dundalk [[Carlingford, County Louth|Carlingford]] || || Y || 6\n|-\n| Dundalk South || || Y || 7\n|-\n|}\nKey:\n{{reflist|group=t}}\n\n===Louth D\u00e1il constituency===\n{{Main|Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)}}\nFor elections to D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann, Louth is represented by the five member [[Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)|Louth constituency]] which takes in the entire county of Louth and two electoral divisions in [[County Meath]]. \nthe [[Electoral (Amendment) Act 2009]] merged the electoral divisions of St.Mary's (Part) and Julianstown, collectively known as \"[[East Meath]]\" in [[County Meath]] with County Louth to form one Louth D\u00e1il constituency.\n\nThe Report on D\u00e1il and European Parliament Constituencies 2007 outlined;<blockquote>''\"by extending the constituency southwards from, and in the environs of, Drogheda and taking in electoral divisions which have extensive linkages with the town. This will allow the inclusion of the town of Drogheda and hinterland areas in a single constituency.\"''<ref>http://www.constituency-commission.ie/docs%5Ccon2007.pdfThis{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> </blockquote>This merger allowed the areas of the Greater Drogheda area in [[County Meath]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.droghedaboro.ie/droghedaboro/downloads/Drogheda%20Issues%20paper.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812081706/http://www.droghedaboro.ie/droghedaboro/downloads/Drogheda%20Issues%20paper.pdf |archivedate=12 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and their combined population of 20,375 to be merged with [[Drogheda]] and County Louth.\n\nFollowing the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]], the constituency elected two TDs for the [[Fine Gael]] party (centre right), and one touchdown each for [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] (centre to centre-right), the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] (centre left) and [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] (left wing).\n\n==Irish language==\nThe area of Omeath was Irish-speaking until the early 20th century. A native dialect of Louth Irish existed there until about 1930 but is now extinct, although recordings have been made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doegen.ie/taxonomy/term/21984|title=The Doegen Records Web Project|date=2009|website=Doegen|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref>\n\n34.07% of the population of County Louth are Irish speakers, with 790 people who use Irish on a daily basis and 2,276 people who use Irish on a weekly basis outside the education system, according to the 2016 census.<ref name=cso2016/>\n\n==People==\n\n===Entertainment===\n*[[Pierce Brosnan]] - Actor, [[James Bond]]\n*[[Eamonn Campbell]] - Member of [[The Dubliners]]\n*[[Andrea Corr]] - Singer, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Caroline Corr]] - Musician, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Jim Corr]] - Musician, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Sharon Corr]] - Musician, [[The Corrs]]\n*[[Evanna Lynch]] -  Actress, ''[[Harry Potter]]''\n*[[Cathy Maguire]] - Singer/songwriter\n*[[John Moore (director)|John Moore]] - Film director\n*[[Gerry O'Connor (fiddle player)|Gerry O'Connor]] - Traditional [[Irish fiddle playing|Irish fiddle]] player\n*[[Colin O'Donoghue]] - Actor, ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''\n\n===Military===\n*[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Francis Leopold McClintock]] [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] - [[Royal Navy]] officer and [[Explorer]]\n*[[Major-general (United Kingdom)|Major-General]] [[Arthur Thomas Moore]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]] - Soldier and recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]]\n*[[James Sheridan (Medal of Honor)]] , [[Quartermaster]] [[United States]] during the [[American Civil War]] - Sailor and recipient of the [[Medal of Honor]] for action at [[Battle of Mobile Bay]]\n\n===Politics===\n*[[Dermot Ahern]] - Politician, [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] for Louth\n*[[James Carroll (Louth politician)|James Carroll]] - Politician, [[Fianna F\u00e1il]], member of [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]] from Louth\n*[[Mark Dearey]] - Politician, [[Green Party (Ireland)|Green Party]] [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]] from Louth\n*[[S\u00e9amus Kirk]] - Politician, [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] for Louth\n*[[John McClintock (1770\u20131855)]], MP for Athlone 1820, for County Louth 1830\u201331\n*[[Brendan McGahon]] - Politician, [[Fine Gael]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] for Louth\n*[[Michael McKevitt]] - Republican dissident leader\n*[[Arthur Morgan (Irish politician)|Arthur Morgan]] - Politician, [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]] for Louth\n\n===Sport===\n*[[Tommy Byrne (racing driver)|Thomas Byrne]] - Former racing driver\n*[[Nick Colgan]] - Footballer, currently playing for [[Grimsby Town F.C.]]\n*[[Kenny Finn]] - [[Irish American]] soccer and Gaelic football player\n*[[Beatrice Hill-Lowe]] - Archer\n*[[Gary Kelly (footballer born 1974)|Gary Kelly]] - Footballer, [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n*[[Rob Kearney|Robert Kearney]] - Irish Rugby player\n*[[Colin Larkin (footballer)|Colin Larkin]] - footballer, [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]]\n*[[Tommy Smyth]] - Football commentator for [[ESPN]]\n*[[Steve Staunton]] - Footballer\n*[[Kevin Thornton (footballer)|Kevin Thornton]] - Footballer\n\n===Misc===\n*[[George Drumgoole Coleman]] - Civil architect\n*[[Peter Rice]] - [[Structural engineer]]\n\n===Gallery===\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Dundalk platform.jpg|Dundalk railway station\nFile:Dkit1 1024x768.jpg|Dundalk IT.\nFile:Cloghafarmore.jpg|[[Clochafarmore|C\u00fa Chulainn's stone]]\nFile:Roche Castle from North West 1.jpg|Castle Roche\nFile:King johns front shadow.jpg|Slive Foy and [[King John's Castle (Carlingford)|King John's Castle]]\nFile:MellifontAbbey.jpg|Mellifont Abbey\nFile:Round Tower, Dromiskin.JPG|Dromiskin Round Tower\nFile:Drogheda - St. Laurences Gate (5638818100).jpg|Drogheda\nFile:Drogheda station.jpg|[[Drogheda railway station]] with the [[Enterprise (train service)|Enterprise]]\nFile:Harbour at Clogher Head - geograph.org.uk - 467123.jpg|Clogherhead Harbour\nFile:Taaffe's Castle and Carlingford Harbour - geograph.org.uk - 986404.jpg|Carlingford Harbour\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of abbeys and priories in the Republic of Ireland#County Louth|List of abbeys and priories in Ireland (County Louth)]]\n*[[List of castles in Ireland#County Louth|List of Castles in Louth]]\n*[[Lord Lieutenant of Louth]]\n*[[High Sheriff of Louth]]\n*[[List of songs about Louth]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n*[http://www.carlingford.net Carlingford town local site]\n*[http://www.drogheda.ie Drogheda Tourism - Official Site of the Drogheda Tourist Office]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120328040012/http://www.dunleertown.net/ Dunleer town portal]\n*[http://www.dunleerparish.ie Dunleer Parish]\n*[http://www.louthcoco.ie Louth Local Authorities]\n*[http://www.omeath.ie Omeath town local site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110716191306/http://tallanstown.com/ Tallanstown Tidy Towns ]\n*[http://www.cso.ie/studentscorner/statsfactslouth.htm CSO Louth]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|North = [[County Armagh]] [[File:Armagh arms.svg|28px]]\n|South = [[County Meath]] [[File:Meath coa.svg|30px]]\n|East = [[Irish Sea]]\n|West = [[County Meath]] [[File:Meath coa.svg|30px]]\n|Northeast = [[County Down]] [[File:Down arms.png|34px]]\n|Northwest = [[County Monaghan]] \n|Centre = County Louth\n}}\n\n{{County Louth}}\n{{Ireland counties}}\n{{Authority control}}\n <!-- see [[WP:SUBCAT#Topic_article_rule]] -->\n\n{{coord|53|50|N|6|30|W|region:IE_type:adm1st_source:GNS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:County Louth| ]]\n[[Category:Leinster|Louth]]\n[[Category:Counties of the Republic of Ireland|Louth]]\n[[Category:Local administrative units of the Republic of Ireland|Louth]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1130-1190 \u2192 1130\u20131190", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/County_Louth"}
{"title_page": "Billy Bryan (baseball)", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Billy Bryan\n|position=[[Catcher]]\n|image=Billy Bryan 1965.jpg\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1938|12|4}}\n|birth_place=[[Morgan, Georgia|Morgan]], [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 12\n|debutyear=1961\n|debutteam=[[Oakland Athletics|Kansas City Athletics]]\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=July 23\n|finalyear=1968\n|finalteam=Washington Senators\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.216\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=41\n|stat3label=[[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=125\n|teams=\n*Kansas City Athletics ({{baseball year|1961}}\u2013{{baseball year|1966}})\n*[[New York Yankees]] (1966\u2013{{baseball year|1967}})\n*[[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] ({{baseball year|1968}})\n}}\n'''William Ronald Bryan''' (born December 4, 1938, in [[Morgan, Georgia]]) is an American former [[Major League Baseball]] [[catcher]].  He was signed by the [[Kansas City Athletics]] in 1960. Bryan played eight seasons in the majors: Kansas City Athletics, 1961\u20131965; [[New York Yankees]], 1966\u20131967; and the [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]], 1968. Bryan stood {{convert|6|ft|4|in}} tall, weighed {{convert|200|lb}}, batted left-handed and threw right-handed.\n\nBryan had some success at the [[minor league baseball|minor league]] level, making the All-Star team for the 1961 Class B [[Northwest League]]<ref>''Baseball Digest'', March 1962, page 85</ref> and hitting 25 [[home runs]], [[runs batted in|knocking in]] 85 [[run (baseball)|runs]], and [[batting average (baseball)|batting]] .295 in the Double-A [[Texas League]] in 1962.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bryanbi01.shtml Baseball Reference]</ref> While Bryan hit for some power in the majors, especially when he was the regular or semi-regular catcher for the Athletics in 1964\u20131965, his batting average was .216 at the Major League level, with 209 career [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 968 [[at bats]], and 283 [[strikeout]]s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=111640|espn=|br=b/bryanbi01|fangraphs=|brm=bryan-003wil|retro=B/Pbryab101}}\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=bryabil001 Venezuelan Professional Baseball League]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryan, Billy}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Albuquerque Dukes players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Industriales de Valencia players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Lewiston Broncs players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Calhoun County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Portland Beavers players]]\n[[Category:Sanford Greyhounds players]]\n[[Category:Spartanburg Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1961\u20131971) players]]\n\n\n{{US-baseball-catcher-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Billy Bryan\n|position=[[Catcher]]\n|image=Billy Bryan 1965.jpg\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1938|12|4}}\n|birth_place=[[Morgan, Georgia|Morgan]], [[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=September 12\n|debutyear=1961\n|debutteam=[[Oakland Athletics|Kansas City Athletics]]\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=July 23\n|finalyear=1968\n|finalteam=Washington Senators\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.216\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=41\n|stat3label=[[Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=125\n|teams=\n*Kansas City Athletics ({{baseball year|1961}}\u2013{{baseball year|1966}})\n*[[New York Yankees]] (1966\u2013{{baseball year|1967}})\n*[[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] ({{baseball year|1968}})\n}}\n'''William Ronald Bryan''' (born December 4, 1938, in [[Morgan, Georgia]]) is an American former [[Major League Baseball]] [[catcher]].  He was signed by the [[Kansas City Athletics]] in 1960. Bryan played eight seasons in the majors: Kansas City Athletics, 1961\u20131965; [[New York Yankees]], 1966\u20131967; and the [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]], 1968. Bryan stood {{convert|6|ft|4|in}} tall, weighed {{convert|200|lb}}, batted left-handed and threw right-handed.\n\nBryan had some success at the [[minor league baseball|minor league]] level, making the All-Star team for the 1961 Class B [[Northwest League]]<ref>''Baseball Digest'', March 1962, page 85</ref> and hitting 25 [[home runs]], [[runs batted in|knocking in]] 85 [[run (baseball)|runs]], and [[batting average (baseball)|batting]] .295 in the Double-A [[Texas League]] in 1962.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bryanbi01.shtml Baseball Reference]</ref> While Bryan hit for some power in the majors, especially when he was the regular or semi-regular catcher for the Athletics in 1964\u20131965, his batting average was .216 at the Major League level, with 209 career [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 968 [[at bats]], and 283 [[strikeout]]s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{baseballstats|mlb=111640|espn=|br=b/bryanbi01|fangraphs=|brm=bryan-003wil|retro=B/Pbryab101}}\n*[http://www.purapelota.com/lvbp/mostrar.php?id=bryabil001 Venezuelan Professional Baseball League]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryan, Billy}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Albuquerque Dukes players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Industriales de Valencia players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Leones del Caracas players]]\n[[Category:Lewiston Broncs players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball catchers]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Calhoun County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Portland Beavers players]]\n[[Category:Sanford Greyhounds players]]\n[[Category:Spartanburg Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Syracuse Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1961\u20131971) players]]\n\n\n{{US-baseball-catcher-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"American baseball player\", overriding Wikidata description \"American baseball player\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Bryan_(baseball)"}
