{"title_page": "Billy Bryan", "text_new": "{{short description|American football center}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{No footnotes|date=January 2015}}\n{{for|the baseball player|Billy Bryan (baseball)}}\n{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| image = ||\n| caption = \n| status = Retired\n| ImageWidth = \n| number = 64, 72\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|6|21|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Burlington, North Carolina]]\n| death_date = \n| College = [[Duke University|Duke]]\n| Position = [[Center (American football)|Center]]\n| DraftedYear = 1977\n| DraftedRound = 4\n| DraftedPick = 101\n| other_teams,other_years = 1x Second Team All-Pro (1985)\n| ProBowls = \n| DatabaseFootball = BRYANBIL02\n| PFR = \n| playing_years1 = 1977\u20131988\n| playing_team1 = [[Denver Broncos]]\n| CBS = \n}}\n'''Billy Bryan''' (born  June 21, 1955 in [[Burlington, North Carolina]]) is a former [[American football]] [[Center (American football)|center]] in the [[National Football League]]. He was drafted by the [[Denver Broncos]] in the 4th round of the [[1977 NFL Draft]] out of [[Duke University]]. He went on to play for the Broncos from 1977\u20131988 and was [[All-Pro]] in 1985.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryan, Bill}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Burlington, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:Duke Blue Devils football players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n\n\n{{offensive-lineman-1950s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{No footnotes|date=January 2015}}\n{{for|the baseball player|Billy Bryan (baseball)}}\n{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| image = ||\n| caption = \n| status = Retired\n| ImageWidth = \n| number = 64, 72\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|6|21|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Burlington, North Carolina]]\n| death_date = \n| College = [[Duke University|Duke]]\n| Position = [[Center (American football)|Center]]\n| DraftedYear = 1977\n| DraftedRound = 4\n| DraftedPick = 101\n| other_teams,other_years = 1x Second Team All-Pro (1985)\n| ProBowls = \n| DatabaseFootball = BRYANBIL02\n| PFR = \n| playing_years1 = 1977\u20131988\n| playing_team1 = [[Denver Broncos]]\n| CBS = \n}}\n'''Billy Bryan''' (born  June 21, 1955 in [[Burlington, North Carolina]]) is a former [[American football]] [[Center (American football)|center]] in the [[National Football League]]. He was drafted by the [[Denver Broncos]] in the 4th round of the [[1977 NFL Draft]] out of [[Duke University]]. He went on to play for the Broncos from 1977\u20131988 and was [[All-Pro]] in 1985.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryan, Bill}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Burlington, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:Duke Blue Devils football players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n\n\n{{offensive-lineman-1950s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"American football center\", overriding Wikidata description \"American football player\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Bryan"}
{"title_page": "List of people considered father or mother of a scientific field", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThe following is a '''list of people who are considered''' a \"'''father'''\" '''or''' \"'''mother'''\" (or \"founding father\" or \"founding mother\") '''of a [[Branches of science|scientific field]]'''. Such people are generally regarded to have made the first significant contributions to and/or delineation of that field; they may also be seen as \"''a''\" rather than \"''the''\" father or mother of the field. Debate over who merits the title can be perennial.\n\n== Science as a whole==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|'''[[Science]] (modern)'''\n| [[Galileo Galilei]] (1564-1642)<ref>Pamela Gossin, ''Encyclopedia of Literature and Science'', 2002.</ref><br /><ref>Finocchiaro, Maurice A. (Fall 2007), \"Book Review\u2014The Person of the Millennium: The Unique Impact of Galileo on World History\", The Historian 69 (3): 601\u2013602</ref><ref>Weidhorn, Manfred (2005). ''The Person of the Millennium: The Unique Impact of Galileo on World History''. Universe, p. 155.</ref>\n| For systemic use of experimentation in [[science]] and contributions to [[scientific method]], [[physics]] and [[observational astronomy]]\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''[[Science]] (ancient)'''\n|[[Thales]] (c. 624/623-c. 548/545 BC)<ref>{{cite book |last=Singer |first=C. |title=A Short History of Science to the 19th century |location= |publisher=Streeter Press |year=2008 |page=35 |isbn=}}<!--(copied from [[Thales]]--></ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Needham |first=C. W. |title=Cerebral Logic: Solving the Problem of Mind and Brain |location= |publisher=Loose Leaf |year=1978 |page=75 |isbn=978-0-398-03754-3}}<!--(copied from [[Thales]]--></ref>\n|Attempted to explain natural phenomena without recourse to [[mythology]]\n\n|-\n|[[Democritus]] (c. 460 - c. 370 BC)\n|[[Atomism|Atomist]]<ref>Pamela Gossin, ''Encyclopedia of Literature and Science'', 2002. <!--(copied from [[Democritus]])--></ref>\n|}\n\n== Natural sciences ==\n=== Biology ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''[[Bacteriology]]'''\n| [[Robert Koch]] (1843-1910){{\\}}[[Ferdinand Cohn]] (1828-1898)<ref>Drews G (1999). \"Ferdinand Cohn, a Founder of Modern Microbiology\". ASM News 65 (8).</ref>{{\\}}[[Louis Pasteur]] (1822-1895)\n|rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"middle\"| First to produce precise, correct descriptions of [[bacteria]].\n</tr>\n|-\n| [[Antonie van Leeuwenhoek]] (1632-1723)<ref name=fm/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Biogeography]]'''\n| [[Alfred Russel Wallace]] (1823-1913)\n| \"...Often described as the Father of Biogeography, Wallace shows the impact of human activity on the natural world.\"<ref>{{cite book |title = Explorers: Tales of Endurance and Exploration |year = 2010 |publisher = Penguin |isbn = 9780756675110 |author = DK Publishing |page = 272 }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Biology]]'''{{NoteTag|A name suggested in 1802 by the German naturalist [[Gottfried Reinhold Treviranus]] and introduced as a scientific term later that year by [[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck]].}}\n| [[Aristotle]] (384-322 BC)\n| <!--(Aristotle:)-->\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Botany]]'''\n| [[Theophrastus]] (c. 371-c. 287 BC)\n| <!--(Theophrastus:)-->\n|-\n|'''[[Cheloniology]]'''\n|[[Archie Carr]] (1909-1987)\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://conserveturtles.org/10693-2/|title=Centennial Tribute to Archie Carr- The Father of Sea Turtle Research & Conservation \u2013 Sea Turtle Conservancy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/feature-story/faces-sea-turtle-conservation-dr-larisa-avens-research-biologist|title=Faces of Sea Turtle Conservation: Dr. Larisa Avens, Research Biologist {{!}} NOAA Fisheries|last=Fisheries|first=NOAA|date=2018-06-12|website=www.fisheries.noaa.gov|language=EN-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoplease.com/people/archie-carr|title=Archie Carr Biography|website=InfoPlease|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mongabay.com/2013/01/telling-the-story-of-the-father-of-sea-turtle-conservation/|title=Telling the story of the father of sea turtle conservation|date=2013-01-21|website=Mongabay Environmental News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://patheyman.com/archie-carr-father-turtle-research/|title=Archie Carr: Father of Turtle Research|last=Heyman|first=Pat|date=2009-11-28|website=Pat Heyman|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Ecology]]'''\n| [[Carl Linnaeus]]{{\\}}[[Ernst Haeckel]]{{\\}}[[Eugenius Warming]]<ref name=\"Goodland (1975)\">{{cite journal|doi=10.2307/3543715|last=Goodland|first=R.J.|date=1975|title=The tropical origin of ecology: Eugen Warming\u2019s jubilee|journal=Oikos|volume=26|issue=2|pages=240\u2013245|jstor=3543715}}</ref>\n| Linnaeus founded an early branch of ecology that he called ''The Economy of Nature'' (1772), Haeckel coined the term \"ecology\" (German: Oekologie, \u00d6kologie) (1866), Warming authored the first book on plant ecology. ''[[Plantesamfund]]'' (1895).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''Modern [[elk]] management'''\n| [[Olaus Murie]] (1889\u20131963)<ref>{{cite website|url=https://medium.com/our-arctic-nation/week-28-wyoming-45206dc95122|website=[[Medium.com]]|author=DanMcIlhenny|title=A Lifelong Passion for Place and Conservation: Wyoming, Alaska, and the Muries\u2019 Arctic Love Affair|date=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n| \n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|rowspan=\"3\"| '''[[Entomology]]'''\n| [[Jan Swammerdam]] (1637-1680)\n| <!--(Swammerdam:)-->{{lower|0.25em|<ref>p. 208, ''A history of social thought'', Paul Hanly Furfey, The Macmillan company, 1942.</ref>}}\n|-\n| [[Johan Christian Fabricius]] (1745-1808)<ref>p. 162, ''Museum: the Macleays, their collections and the search for order'', Robyn Stacey, Ashley Hay, Cambridge University Press, 2007, {{ISBN|0-521-87453-X}}.</ref>\n| Fabricius described and published information on over 10,000 insects and refined Linnaeus's system of classification.\n|-\n| [[William Kirby (entomologist)|William Kirby]] (1759-1850)\n| <!--(Kirby:)-->{{lower|0.25em|<ref>p. 118, ''The fossil hunter: dinosaurs, evolution, and the woman whose discoveries changed the world'', Shelley Emling, Macmillan, 2009, {{ISBN|0-230-61156-7}}.</ref>}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Ethology]]'''\n| [[Nikolaas Tinbergen]]<br />[[Karl von Frisch]]<br /> [[Konrad Lorenz]]\n| The modern discipline of [[ethology]] is generally considered to have begun during the 1930s with the work of [[Nikolaas Tinbergen]], [[Konrad Lorenz]] and [[Karl von Frisch]], joint awardees of the 1973 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/1973/index.html|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1973|work=Nobelprize.org.|accessdate=9 September 2016|quote=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 1973 was awarded jointly to Karl von Frisch, Konrad Lorenz and Nikolaas Tinbergen 'for their discoveries concerning organization and elicitation of individual and social behaviour patterns'.}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''{{hlist |[[Evolution]] |[[Natural selection]]}}'''\n| [[Charles Darwin]]<!--\n    --><ref>Darwin, Charles (1842, published 1909), \"Pencil Sketch of 1842\", in Darwin, Francis, The foundations of The origin of species: Two essays written in 1842 and 1844., Cambridge University Press, <http://darwin-online.org.uk/content/frameset?itemID=F1556&viewtype=text&pageseq=1> Retrieved on 2006-12-15</ref><!--\n    --><ref>Moore, James (2006), 