hive-date=5 June 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Molecular biophysics]]'''\n| [[Gopalasamudram Narayana Iyer Ramachandran]]<ref>{{citation |title=Indian science slows down: The decline of open-ended research |first=Gangan |last=Prathap |journal=[[Current Science]] |volume=86 |issue=6 |date=March 2004 |pages=768\u2013769 [768]}}</ref>\n| Founded the [world's first?] molecular biophysics unit (1970).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Paleontology]]'''\n| [[Leonardo da Vinci]] (1452-1519)<br />[[George Cuvier]] (1769-1832)\n| {{lower|0.25em|<ref>p. 287, ''On social structure and science'' (volume 1996 of ''Heritage of sociology''), Robert King Merton and Piotr Sztompka, University of Chicago Press, 1996, {{ISBN|0-226-52071-4}}.</ref>}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Parasitology]]'''\n| [[Francesco Redi]] (1626-1697)\n| The founder of experimental biology and the first person to challenge the theory of spontaneous generation by demonstrating that maggots come from eggs of flies.<ref name=lev>{{cite web |vauthors=Levine R, Evers C |title=The Slow Death of Spontaneous Generation (1668-1859) |url= http://www.accessexcellence.org/RC/AB/BC/Spontaneous_Generation.php|accessdate=2013-04-18 |date=  }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Protozoology]]'''\n| [[Antonie van Leeuwenhoek]] (1632-1723)<ref name=fm>p. 18, ''Foundations in microbiology: basic principles'', Kathleen Park Talaro, 6th ed., international ed., McGraw-Hill, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-07-126232-3}}.</ref>\n| First to produce precise, correct descriptions of [[protozoa]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Taxonomy (biology)|Taxonomy]]'''\n| [[Carl Linnaeus]] (1707-1778)<ref>Hovey, Edmund Otis, \"The Bicentenary of the Birth of Carolus Linnaeus\", New York: New York Academy of Sciences, 1908.</ref>\n| Devised the system of naming living organisms that became universally accepted in the scientific world.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Virology]]'''\n| [[Dmitry Ivanovsky]] <br /> [[Martinus Beijerinck]]\n| The first men to discover [[viruses]] (1892).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Zoology]]'''\n| [[Aristotle]] (384-322 BC)\n| His contributions to the field include vast quantities of information about the variety, structure, and behavior of animals\n|}\n\n===Chemistry===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Atomic theory]]''' (early)\n| [[Democritus]] ((c. 460 - c. 370 BC) )<ref>{{cite book |first=Murray N. |last=Rothbard |authorlink=Murray Rothbard |title=Economic thought before Adam Smith: An Austrian Perspective on the History of Economic Thought |url=https://mises.org/books/histofthought1.pdf |publisher=Edward Elgar |page=10 |location=Cheltnam, UK |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-945466-48-2}}</ref>\n| Founder of [[atomism]] in cosmology.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''Atomic theory''' (modern)\n| [[Roger Joseph Boscovich|Father Roger Boscovich]] (1711-1787)<ref>[[Thomas Woods|Woods, Thomas]]. ''How the Catholic Church Built Western Civilization'', p 4 & 107. (Washington, DC: Regenery, 2005); {{ISBN|0-89526-038-7}}.</ref>\n| First coherent description of atomic theory.\n|-\n| [[John Dalton]] (1766-1844)<ref>{{cite book |first=Elizabeth C. |last=Patterson |authorlink=Elizabeth C. Patterson |title=John Dalton and the Atomic Theory |publisher=Anchor |page=10 |location=Garden City, New York |year=1970|title-link=John Dalton and the Atomic Theory }}</ref>\n| First scientific description of the atom as a building block for more complex structures.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Chemical thermodynamics]]''' (modern)\n| [[Gilbert N. Lewis|Gilbert Lewis]]{{\\}}[[Willard Gibbs]]{{\\}}[[Merle Randall]]{{\\}}[[Edward Guggenheim]]<ref name=\"Ott\">{{cite book |last=Ott |first=Bevan, J. |author2=Boerio-Goates, Juliana |year=2001 |title=Chemical Thermodynamics - Principles and Applications |isbn=978-0-12-530990-5}}</ref>\n| ''Thermodynamics and the Free Energy of Chemical Substances'' (1923) and ''Modern Thermodynamics by the Methods of Willard Gibbs'' (1933), which made a major contribution to the use of [[thermodynamics]] in [[chemistry]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Chemistry]]''' (early)\n| [[Jabir ibn Hayyan|Jabir (\"Geber\") ibn Hayyan {{small|(died 815)}}]]<!--\n     --><ref>{{citation |first=Zygmunt S. |last=Derewenda |year=2007 |title=On wine, chirality and crystallography |journal=Acta Crystallographica A |volume=64 |issue=Pt 1 |pages=246\u2013258 [247] |doi=10.1107/s0108767307054293 |pmid=18156689|bibcode=2008AcCrA..64..246D }}</ref><!--\n     --><ref>John Warren (2005). \"War and the Cultural Heritage of Iraq: a sadly mismanaged affair\", ''Third World Quarterly'', Volume 26, Issue 4 & 5, p. 815-830.</ref><!--\n     --><ref>Dr. A. Zahoor (1997). [http://www.unhas.ac.id/~rhiza/saintis/haiyan.html JABIR IBN HAIYAN (Geber)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080630061235/http://www.unhas.ac.id/~rhiza/saintis/haiyan.html |date=2008-06-30 }}. [[University of Indonesia]].</ref><!--\n     --><ref>Paul Vallely. [http://news.independent.co.uk/world/science_technology/article350594.ece How Islamic inventors changed the world.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517013534/http://news.independent.co.uk/world/science_technology/article350594.ece |date=2008-05-17 }} ''[[The Independent]]''.</ref>\n| Introduced the [[Scientific method|experimental method]] to [[Alchemy (Islam)|Islamic alchemy]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|rowspan=\"4\"| '''Chemistry''' (modern)\n| [[Antoine Lavoisier]]<ref name=\"Kim\">{{cite book |last=Kim |first=Mi Gyung |year=2003 |title=Affinity, That Elusive Dream - A Genealogy of the Chemical Revolution (Epilogue: A Tale of Three Fathers) |isbn=978-0-262-11273-4}}</ref>\n| <!--(Lavoisier:)-->''Elements of Chemistry'' (1787)\n|-\n| [[Robert Boyle]]<ref name=\"Kim\"/>\n| <!--(Boyle:)-->''The Sceptical Chymist'' (1661)\n|-\n| [[J\u00f6ns Jakob Berzelius|J\u00f6ns Berzelius]]<ref>[http://scienceworld.wolfram.com/biography/Berzelius.html Berzelius, J\u00f6ns (1779\u20131848)] - Eric Weisstein's World of Scientific Biography</ref><ref>[http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9078919 Jons Jacob] - Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online, 2 Aug 2007</ref>\n| <!--(Berzelius:)-->Development of chemical nomenclature (1800s)\n|-\n| [[John Dalton]]<ref name=\"Kim\"/>\n| <!--(Dalton:)-->Revival of [[atomic theory]] (1803)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Green chemistry]]'''\n| [[Paul Anastas]] (born 1962)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/system/404.html|title=404: Not Found|website=American Chemical Society|access-date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n| Design and manufacture of chemicals that are non-hazardous and environmentally benign.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Nuclear chemistry]]'''\n| [[Otto Hahn]]<ref>O. Hahn and F. Strassmann ''\u00dcber den Nachweis und das Verhalten der bei der Bestrahlung des Urans mittels Neutronen entstehenden Erdalkalimetalle'' (''On the detection and characteristics of the alkaline earth metals formed by irradiation of uranium with neutrons''), ''Naturwissenschaften'' Volume 27, Number 1, 11-15 (1939). The authors were identified as being at the Kaiser-Wilhelm-Institut f\u00fcr Chemie, Berlin-Dahlem. Received 22 December 1938.</ref>\n| {{hlist |''[[Applied Radiochemistry]]'' (1936) |First person to split an atomic nucleus ([[nuclear fission]], 1938) |[[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] for this discovery (1944)}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Periodic table]]'''\n| [[Dmitri Mendeleev]]<ref>''Chemistry Contexts''. by Irwin, D; Farrelly, R; Garnett, P. Longman Sciences, (2001)</ref>\n| Arranged the sixty-six elements known at the time in order of [[atomic weight]] by periodic intervals (1869).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|rowspan=\"5\"| '''[[Physical chemistry]]'''\n| [[Mikhail Lomonosov]]\n| The first to read lectures in physical chemistry and coin the term (1752).\n|-\n| [[Jacobus van 't Hoff]] (1852-1911)\n| Jacobus van 't Hoff is considered one of the founders of the discipline of [[physical chemistry]]. His work helped found the discipline as it is today.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Meijer |first=E. W. | title=Jacobus Henricus van 't Hoff; Hundred Years of Impact on Stereochemistry in the Netherlands | journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition | volume= 40 | issue= 20 | pages=3783\u20133789 | year=2001 | doi=10.1002/1521-3773(20011015)40:20<3783::AID-ANIE3783>3.0.CO;2-J | pmid=11668534}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Spek |first=Trienke M. van der | title=Selling a Theory: The Role of Molecular Models in J. H. van 't Hoff's Stereochemistry Theory | journal=Annals of Science | volume= 63 | issue= 2 | pages = 157\u2013177 | year=2006 | doi=10.1080/00033790500480816}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Kreuzfeld |first=HJ |last2=Hateley |first2=MJ. | title=125 years of enantiomers: back to the roots Jacobus Henricus van 't Hoff 1852\u20131911| journal=Enantiomer | volume= 4 | issue= 6 | pages=491\u20136 | year=1999 | pmid=10672458}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Svante Arrhenius]]<ref>{{cite book |title=Science in the Early Twentieth Century: An Encyclopedia |year=2005 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9781851096657 |author=Jacob Darwin Hamblin |page=9 |quote=His interest in both fields would serve him well, because he became a principal founder of physical chemistry.}}</ref>\n| Devised much of the theoretical foundation for [[physical chemistry]]. ''[[On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances]]'' (1876), ''Thermodynamik chemischer Vorgange'' (1882).\n|-\n| [[Wilhelm Ostwald]] (1853-1932)\n| \"Wilhelm Ostwald is considered one of the founders of the discipline of physical chemistry...\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of World Scientists |year=2010 |publisher=Infobase Publishing |isbn=9781438118826 |author=Elizabeth H. Oakes |page=562 |quote=}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Hermann von Helmholtz]] (1821-1894)\n| {{lower|0.25em|{{big|{{noitalic|'''{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}'''}}}}}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Earth sciences===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Geochemistry]]''' (modern)\n| [[Victor Goldschmidt]] (1888-1947)\n| For developing the [[Goldschmidt classification]] of elements.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| Early '''[[geodesy]]''' (mathematical geography)\n| [[Eratosthenes]] (c.276-195/4 BC)<ref>p. 12, ''Plotting the globe: stories of meridians, parallels, and the international date line'', Avraham Ariel and Nora Ariel Berger, Greenwood Publishing Group, 2006, {{ISBN|0-275-98895-3}}.</ref><ref>p. 389, \"Eratosthenes\", D. R. Dicks, in ''Dictionary of Scientific Biography'', ed. Charles Coulston Gillispie, vol. 4, New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1971.</ref>\n|Eratosthenes was first to write the word ''Geography'' (from Geo- and -graphy, literally \"writing about the Earth\")\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| Modern '''[[geodesy]]'''\n| [[Al-Biruni]] (973-c.1050)<ref>Ahmed, Akbar S. (1984). \"Al-Beruni: The First Anthropologist\". RAIN. 60 (60): 9\u201310. {{doi|10.2307/3033407}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iJ0bDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA12&lpg=PA12&dq=al+biruni+father+of+geodesy#v=onepage&q=al+biruni+father+of+geodesy&f=false|title=Interpreting Our World: 100 Discoveries That Revolutionized Geography: 100 Discoveries That Revolutionized Geography|first=Joseph J. Kerski|last=Ph.D|date=17 October 2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|access-date=15 January 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9781610699204}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Geology]]''' (modern)\n| {{unbulleted list\n  | [[Nicolas Steno]] (1638-1686)<ref name=\"Woods96\">[[Thomas Woods|Woods, Thomas]]. ''How the Catholic Church Built Western Civilization'', p 4 & 96. (Washington, DC: Regenery, 2005); {{ISBN|0-89526-038-7}}.</ref>\n  | [[James Hutton]] (1726-1797)<ref>Jack Repcheck: ''The Man Who Found Time: James Hutton 