0208-3 |pages=9}}</ref>\n  | \"In addition to being known as the ''Father of Modern Chemistry'', Lavoisier is also considered the ''Father of Modern Nutrition'', as the first to discover the metabolism that occurs inside the human body...\"<ref>''Lavoisier, Antoine.'' Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. 2007. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. 24 July 2007.</ref>\n }}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Organ transplantation]]'''\n|[[Thomas Starzl]]<ref name=\"Trib\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/pittsburgh/s_664527.html |title=Starzl, Tribune-Review reporters claim Carnegie Science Awards |first=Mike |last=Cronin |date=2010-01-29 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Tribune-Review |accessdate=2010-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130215144/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/pittsburgh/s_664527.html |archive-date=2010-01-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (1926-2017)\n| Performed the first human liver transplant and established the clinical utility of anti-rejection drugs including [[ciclosporin]]. Developed major advances in organ preservation,  procurement and transplantation.\n|-\n|'''[[Orthopedic surgery]]''' (modern)\n|[[Hugh Owen Thomas]]<ref>p. 533, ''Orthopaedic Pathology'', Peter G. Bullough, Elsevier Health Sciences, 2009, 5th ed., {{ISBN|03-23074-73-1}}.</ref> (1834-1891)\n| He stressed the importance of rest in treatment and was responsible for many landmark contributions to orthopaedic surgery. He was especially celebrated for his design and use of splints; the famous Thomas knee splint was still in wide use at the end of World War II.\n|-\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Psychology]]''' (experimental)\n|[[Wilhelm Wundt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allpsych.com/biographies/wundt.html|title=Wilhelm Wundt - AllPsych|website=AllPsych.com|access-date=15 January 2018}}</ref>(1832-1920)\n| Founded the first [[laboratory]] for psychological research.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Pediatrics]]'''\n|[[Muhammad ibn Zakar\u012bya R\u0101zi|Muhammad ibn Zakar\u012bya R\u0101zi (\"Rhazes\")]]<ref>{{cite journal |author=Tschanz David W. |year=2003 |title=Arab Roots of European Medicine |url= |journal=Heart Views |volume=4 |issue= |page=2}}</ref> (854\u2013925 CE)\n| Wrote ''The Diseases of Children'', the first book to deal with pediatrics as an independent field.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Physiology]]'''\n|[[Fran\u00e7ois Magendie]]\n|''Pr\u00e9cis \u00e9lementaire de Physiologie'' (1816)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Physical culture]]'''\n|[[Bernarr Macfadden]] (1868-1955)\n| \"It delighted the heart of our old friend Bernarr Macfadden, 'the Father of Physical Culture,' when we told him how much athletic activity and good sportsmanship had to do with the rehabilitation of boys.\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Oursler |first=Fulton |authorlink=Fulton Oursler |author2=Will Oursler |authorlink2=Will Oursler |year=1949 |title=Father Flanagan of Boys Town |publisher=Doubleday |location= |id= |page=270}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Plastic surgery]]'''\n|{{unbulleted list\n | [[Sushruta]]<ref name=\"Singh\">A. Singh and D. Sarangi (2003). \"We need to think and act\", ''Indian Journal of Plastic Surgery''.</ref><ref name=\"Longfellow\">H. W. Longfellow (2002). \"History of Plastic Surgery in India\", ''Journal of Postgraduate Medicine''.</ref> (sixth century?)\n | [[Harold Gillies]] (1882-1960)\n}}\n| Wrote the ''[[Sushruta Samhita]]'' (878 CE?)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Psychoanalysis]]'''\n|[[Sigmund Freud]] (1856-1939)\n|{{lower|0.25em|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iep.utm.edu/f/freud.htm|title=Freud, Sigmund - Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy|website=www.iep.UTM.edu|access-date=15 January 2018}}</ref>}}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Psychophysics]]'''\n|{{unbulleted list\n| [[Ernst Heinrich Weber]] (1795-1878)|[[Gustav Fechner]] (1801-1887)<ref>{{citation |last=Aaen-Stockdale |first=Craig |year=2008 |title=Ibn al-Haytham and psychophysics |journal=Perception |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=636\u2013638 |doi=10.1068/p5940 |pmid=18546671}}</ref>}}\n|''Elements of Psychophysics'' (1860)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Space medicine]]'''\n|[[Hubertus Strughold]] (1898-1986)\n| \"After [[Wernher von Braun]], he was the top Nazi scientist employed by the American government, and he was subsequently hailed by NASA as the 'father of space medicine'\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Lee |first=Martin A. |authorlink= |author2=Bruce Shlain |year=1986 |title=Acid Dreams: The Complete Social History of LSD: The CIA, the Sixties, and Beyond |publisher=Grove Press |location= |isbn=978-0-8021-3062-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/aciddreamscomple00leem/page/6 6] |url=https://archive.org/details/aciddreamscomple00leem/page/6 }}. See also [[Harry George Armstrong|Harry Armstrong]].</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n|'''[[Surgery]]''' (early)\n|[[Sushruta]]<ref name=\"Singh\" /><ref name=\"Longfellow\" /> (sixth century?)\n| Wrote the ''[[Sushruta Samhita]]'' (878 CE?)\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|'''[[Surgery]]''' (modern)\n|{{unbulleted list\n  | [[Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi|Abu al-Qasim (\"Abulcasis\") al-Zahrawi]]<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Martin-Araguz A. |author2=Bustamante-Martinez C. |author3=Fernandez-Armayor Ajo V. |author4=Moreno-Martinez J. M. |year=2002 |title=Neuroscience in al-Andalus and its influence on medieval scholastic medicine |url= |journal=Revista de Neurolog\u00eda |volume=34 |issue=9| pages=877\u2013892 |pmid=12134355|doi=10.33588/rn.3409.2001382 }}</ref> (936-1013)\n  | [[Guy de Chauliac]]<ref>p. 283, ''[https://archive.org/details/oldtimemakersme02walsgoog Old-Time Makers of Medicine]'', James J. Walsh, New York: Fordham University Press, 1911.</ref> (1300-1368)\n  | [[Ambroise Par\u00e9]] (1510-1590)\n  | [[John Hunter (surgeon)|John Hunter]] (1728-1793)\n  | [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]] (1827-1912)\n  | [[William Stewart Halsted]] (1852-1922)\n  | '''''See also [[Father of modern surgery]]'''''\n }}\n|{{unbulleted list\n  |<!--(Abulcasis:)-->''