kable Discoveries!, Cambridge University Press - 1996. page 1</ref>\n| Book: ''[[De Magnete]]'' (1600)<br />Discovered [[electromagnetic induction]] (1831)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Classical electromagnetism|Electrodynamics]]'''\n|[[Andr\u00e9-Marie Amp\u00e8re]]<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/21416/Andre-Marie-Ampere Andr\u00e9-Marie Amp\u00e8re] - Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica</ref>\n|Book: ''Memoir on the Mathematical Theory of Electrodynamic Phenomena, Uniquely Deduced from Experience'' (1827)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Energetics]]'''\n| [[Willard Gibbs]]<ref>{{Cite EB1911 |wstitle=Gibbs, Josiah Willard |volume=11 |page=937}}</ref>\n| Publication: ''[[On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances]]'' (1876)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Experimental physics]]''' (founder)\n| [[Alhazen|Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen)]]<ref>{{citation|first=R\u00fcdiger|last=Thiele|year=2005|title=In Memoriam: Matthias Schramm|journal=Arabic Sciences and Philosophy|volume=15|issue=2|pages=329\u2013331|doi=10.1017/S0957423905000214}}</ref><ref name=\"Thiele\">{{citation|first=R\u00fcdiger|last=Thiele|title=In Memoriam: Matthias Schramm, 1928\u20132005|journal=Historia Mathematica|volume=32|issue=3|date=August 2005|pages=271\u2013274|doi=10.1016/j.hm.2005.05.002}}</ref>\n| For introducing [[experiment]]al method into [[physics]] with his ''[[Book of Optics]]'' (1021)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Meteoritics]]'''\n| [[Ernst Chladni]]<ref>{{cite journal |author=McCoy, T. J.; Steele, I. M.; Keil, K.; Leonard, B. F.; Endress, M. |title=Chladniite: A New Mineral Honoring the Father of Meteoritics |journal=Meteoritics |volume=28 |pages=394 |bibcode=1993Metic..28Q.394M |issue=3 |last2=Steele |last3=Keil |last4=Leonard |last5=Endress |year=1993}}</ref>\n| First to publish in modern Western thought (in 1794) the then audacious idea that meteorites are rocks from space.<ref>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Henry Smith|title=A history of science|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hNEFAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA168|volume=3|year=1904|publisher=Harper|page=168ff|chapter=5|isbn=0-250-40142-8}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''Modern [[astronomy]]'''\n| [[Nicolaus Copernicus]]<ref>Danielson, Dennis, \"The First Copernican: Georg Joachim Rheticus and the Rise of the Copernican Revolution\", Walker & Company, 2006</ref>\n|Developed the first explicit [[Heliocentrism|heliocentric model]] in ''[[De revolutionibus orbium coelestium]]'' (1543)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Nuclear physics]]'''\n| [[Ernest Rutherford, 1st Baron Rutherford of Nelson|Ernest Rutherford]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Pasachoff |first=Naomi |year=2005 |title=Ernest Rutherford: Father Of Nuclear Science (Great Minds of Science) |location= |isbn=978-0-7660-2441-0}}</ref>\n|Developed the [[Rutherford atom]] model (1909)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Nuclear science]]'''\n| [[Marie Curie]]<br />[[Pierre Curie]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaea.org/Resources/Women/famous.html|title=Resources<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=IAEA.org|access-date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Optics]]'''\n| [[Alhazen|Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen)]]<ref>R. L. Verma (1969). ''Al-Hazen: father of modern optics''.</ref>\n| Correctly explained [[Visual perception|vision]] and carried out the first [[experiment]]s on [[light]] and optics in the ''[[Book of Optics]]'' (1021).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Physics]] (early)'''\n| [[Alhazen|Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen)]]<ref>Jim Al-Khalili, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/7810846.stm The 'first true scientist'], BBC.co.uk, 4 January 2009.</ref><br>[[Francis Bacon]]<ref>MLA style:\n\"Bacon, Francis, Viscount Saint Alban, Baron of Verulam.\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. 2007. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. 28 Dec. 2007  <http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9108408>. APA style:\nBacon, Francis, Viscount Saint Alban, Baron of Verulam. (2007).</ref>\n| Alhazen developed rigorous experimental methods of controlled scientific testing to verify theoretical hypotheses and substantiate inductive conjectures.\nDeveloped [[Baconian method]] in his ''[[Novum Organum]]'' (1620).\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Physical cosmology]]'''\n| [[Georges Lema\u00eetre]] (founder)<br />\n[[Albert Einstein]]<br />\n[[Henrietta Leavitt]] (mother)<ref name=\"physics.fsu.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.physics.fsu.edu/users/ProsperH/AST3033/Cosmology.htm|title=Milestones in the birth of Cosmology|website=FSU.edu|access-date=15 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803064607/http://www.physics.fsu.edu/users/ProsperH/AST3033/Cosmology.htm|archive-date=3 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><br />\n[[Edwin Hubble]] (father)<ref name=\"physics.fsu.edu\"/>\n| Monsignor Lema\u00eetre is considered \u201cthe Father of the Big Bang\u201d and the first to derive what is now known as Hubble's law. Leavitt discovered [[Cepheid variables]], the \"[[Standard Candle]]\" by which Hubble later determined galactic distances. Einstein's general theory of relativity is usually recognized as the theoretic foundation of modern cosmology.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Physics]] (modern)'''\n| [[Galileo Galilei]]<ref>Weidhorn, Manfred (2005). The Person of the Millennium: The Unique Impact of Galileo on World History. iUniverse, p. 155. {{ISBN|0-595-36877-8}}.</ref>\n| His development and extensive use of experimental physics, e.g. the [[telescope]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Plasma physics]]'''\n| [[Irving Langmuir]]<br />[[Hannes Alfv\u00e9n]]<ref>R. Fitzpatrick (2011). ''A brief history of plasma physics''.</ref>\n| Langmuir first described ionised gas as [[plasma (physics)|plasma]] and observed fundamental plasma vibrations, [[Langmuir waves]].<br />Alfv\u00e9n pioneered the theoretical description of plasma by developing [[magnetohydrodynamics]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Quantum mechanics]]'''\n| [[Max Karl Ernst Ludwig Planck|Max Planck]]<ref>Heilbron, J. L. ''The Dilemmas of an Upright Man: Max Planck and the Fortunes of German Science'' (Harvard, 2000)</ref>\n| Stated that [[Electromagnetic radiation|electromagnetic]] energy could be emitted only in [[Quantization (physics)|quantized]] form\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Theory of relativity|Relativity]]'''\n| [[Albert Einstein]] (founder)<ref name=\"Relativity. The Special and General Theory. A Popular Exposition. NewYork: Crown Publishers, 1961.\">[http://archive.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/NumRel/Biblio.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514130104/http://archive.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/NumRel/Biblio.html |date=2008-05-14 }}. URL accessed December 5, 2006.</ref>\n| Pioneered [[special relativity]] (1905) and [[general relativity]] (1915)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[String Theory]]'''\n| [[Leonard Susskind]]\n| He was the first to introduce the idea of the string theory landscape in 2003.\n|- valign=\"top\n| '''[[Spaceflight]]''' '''([[rocket]]ry)'''\n| [[Robert Hutchings Goddard]]<br />[[Konstantin Tsiolkovsky]]<br />[[Hermann Oberth]]\n| Goddard launched the first liquid-fueled rocket.<br />Tsiolkovsky created the [[Tsiolkovsky rocket equation]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Thermodynamics]]'''\n| [[Nicolas L\u00e9onard Sadi Carnot|Sadi Carnot]] (founder)<ref>{{cite book |author=Perrot, Pierre |title=A to Z of Thermodynamics |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1998 |isbn=978-0-19-856552-9}}</ref>\n| Publication: ''On the Motive Power of Fire and Machines Fitted to Develop that Power'' (1824)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|}\n\n== Formal sciences ==\n===Mathematics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Algebra]]'''<br />{{small|(see also [[History of Algebra#The father of algebra|The father of algebra]])}}\n|  [[Muhammad ibn M\u016bs\u0101 al-Khw\u0101rizm\u012b|Muhammad Al-Khwarizmi (Algorismi)]]<ref>Solomon Gandz (1936), ''The sources of al-Khwarizmi's algebra'', Osiris '''I''', p. 263\u2013277: \"In a sense, Khwarizmi is more entitled to be called ''the father of algebra'' than Diophantus, because Khwarizmi is the first to teach algebra in an elementary form and for its own sake, Diophantus is primarily concerned with the theory of numbers.\"</ref> [[Brahmagupta]]<ref name=\"Nanisetti\">Serish Nanisetti, [http://www.hindu.com/yw/2006/06/23/stories/2006062301070600.htm Father of algorithms and algebra], ''[[The Hindu]]'', June 23, 2006.</ref><br />[[Diophantus]]<ref name=\"Carl Boyer For Al Khwarizmi\">{{cite book|first=Carl B.|last=Boyer|authorlink=Carl Benjamin Boyer|title=A History of Mathematics|edition=Second|publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc.|year=1991|chapter=The Arabic Hegemony|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofmathema00boye/page/228 228]|isbn=978-0-471-54397-8|quote=Diophantus sometimes is called \"the father of algebra,\" but this title more appropriately belongs to al-Khwarizmi. It is true that in two respects the work of al-Khwarizmi represented a retrogression from that of Diophantus. First, it is on a far more elementary level than that found in the Diophantine problems and, second, the algebra of al-naren is thoroughly rhetorical, with none of the syncopation found in the Greek ''Arithmetica'' or in Brahmagupta's work. Even numbers were written out in words rather than symbols! It is quite unlikely that al-Khwarizmi knew of the work of Diophantus, but he must have been familiar with at least the astronomical and computational portions of Brahmagupta; yet neither al-Khwarizmi nor other Arabic scholars made use of syncopation or of negative numbers.|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofmathema00boye/page/228}}</ref><ref name=\"John Derbyshire For Diophantus\">{{cite book|first=John|last=Derbyshire|authorlink=John Derbyshire|title=Unknown Quantity: A Real And Imaginary History of Algebra|publisher=Joseph Henry Press|year=2006|chapter=The Father of Algebra|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780309096577/page/31 31]|isbn=978-0-309-09657-7|quote=Diophantus, the father of algebra, in whose honor I have named this chapter, lived in Alexandria, in Roman Egypt, in either the 1st, the 2nd, or the 3rd century CE.|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780309096577/page/31}}</ref>\n| Full exposition of solving [[quadratic equation]]s in his ''[[The Compendious Book on Calculation by Completion and Balancing|Al-Jabr]]'' and recognized algebra as an independent discipline.<br />First use of symbolism ([[History of algebra#Diophantine algebra|syncopation]]) in his ''[[Arithmetica]]''.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Algebraic topology]]'''\n| [[Henri Poincar\u00e9]]<ref>{{cite book|title=History of Topology|year=1999|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9780444823755|editor=Ioan Mackenzie James|page=544|quote=Poincar\u00e9: the founder of algebraic topology}}</ref>\n| Published ''[[Analysis Situs (paper)|Analysis Situs]]'' in 1895,<ref>Poincar\u00e9, Henri, \"Analysis situs\", Journal de l'\u00c9cole Polytechnique ser 2, 1 (1895) pp. 1\u2013123</ref> introducing the concepts of [[homotopy]] and [[homology (mathematics)|homology]], which are now considered part of [[algebraic topology]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Mathematical analysis|Analysis]]'''\n| [[Augustin-Louis Cauchy]]<ref>p. 750, ''Rudiments of Mathematics Part 1'', M. N. Mukherjee, P. Mukhopadhyay, S. Sinha Roy & U. Dasgupta, Academic Publishers, 2008, 5th ed., {{ISBN|81-89781-54-5}}.</ref><br />[[Karl Weierstrass]]<ref>p. 147, ''Collisions, rings, and other Newtonian N-body problems'', [[Donald G. Saari]], American Mathematical Society, 2005, {{ISBN|0-8218-3250-6}}.</ref>\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Analytic geometry]]'''\n| [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]]<br />[[Pierre de Fermat]]<ref>[[Jan Gullberg|Gullberg, Jan]] (1997). Mathematics From The Birth Of Numbers. W. W. Norton</ref> (founders)\n|For their independent invention of the [[Cartesian Coordinate System]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Calculus]]'''\n| [[Isaac Newton]]<ref>Bell, E.T. [1937] (1986). Men of Mathematics, Touchstone edition, New York: Simon & Schuster, pp. 91\u20132.</ref><br />[[Gottfried Leibniz]]\n| See [[Leibniz and Newton calculus controversy]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Mathematical analysis|Classical analysis]]'''\n| [[Madhava of Sangamagrama]]<ref>George Gheverghese Joseph (2000). ''The Crest of the Peacock''. [[Princeton University Press]].</ref>\n| Developed [[Taylor series]] expansions of [[trigonometric function]]s\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|'''[[Computer science]]'''\n| [[Charles Babbage]]<br />[[Alan Turing]]\n| In the [[history of computer science]] Babbage is often regarded as one of the first pioneers of computing and Turing invented the principle of the modern computer and the stored program concept that almost all modern day computers use.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Computer programming]]'''\n| [[Ada Lovelace]]\n|Work on Charles Babbage's proposed mechanical general-purpose computer, the Analytical Engine\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|'''[[Cryptanalysis]]'''\n| [[Al-Kindi]]<ref>{{cite news|title=The man who cracked the Kama Sutra code|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/science-news/4754214/The-man-who-cracked-the-Kama-Sutra-code.html|date=4 October 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Coles|first1=Michael|last2=Landrum|first2=Rodney|title=Expert SQL Server 2008 Encryption|date=2011|publisher=Apress|isbn=9781430233657|url=https://books.google.com/?id=62nISF6l7dwC&pg=PA9&dq=al+kindi+cryptanalysis#v=onepage&q=al%20kindi%20cryptanalysis%20founder&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite thesis |url=http://www.theses.fr/2015NICE4141.pdf |type=PhD |last=BIN NGAH |first=Lutfi A. |date=2015|page=16 |title=All-optical synchronization for quantum networking. |publisher=UNIVERSIT\u00c9 NICE SOPHIA ANTIPOLIS}}</ref>\n|Developed the first code breaking algorithm based on [[frequency analysis]]. He wrote a book entitled \"Manuscript on Deciphering Cryptographic Messages\", containing detailed discussions on [[statistics]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Descriptive geometry]]'''\n| [[Gaspard Monge]]<ref>\"Monge, Gaspard, comte de Peluse.\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica. 2007. Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. 24 Aug. 2007  <http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9053349>.</ref><br />(founder)\n|Developed a graphical protocol that creates three-dimensional virtual space on a two-dimensional plane\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Fractal geometry]]'''\n| [[Beno\u00eet B. Mandelbrot]]\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Geometry]]'''\n| [[Euclid]]<ref>Artmann, Benno (1999). Euclid: The Creation of Mathematics. New York: Springer.</ref>\n| ''[[Euclid's Elements]]'' deduced the principles of [[Euclidean geometry]] from a set of [[axioms]].\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Graph theory]]'''\n| [[Leonhard Euler]]<ref>Biggs, N. Lloyd, E. and Wilson, R. (1986). Graph Theory, 1736-1936 . London: Oxford University Press</ref>\n| See [[Seven Bridges of K\u00f6nigsberg]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Italian school of algebraic geometry]]'''\n| [[Corrado Segre]]<ref>[[H.F. Baker]] (1926), \"Corrado Segre\", [[Journal of the London Mathematical Society]] 1:269</ref>\n| Publications and students developing [[algebraic geometry]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Modern algebra]]'''\n| [[Emmy Noether]]<ref>{{citation| last=Ne'eman | first=Yuval|contribution=The Impact of Emmy Noether's Theorems on XXIst Century Physics|pages=83\u2013101 | title=The Heritage of Emmy Noether|editor-first= M.|editor-last =Teicher|editor-link= Mina Teicher |series=Israel Mathematical Conference Proceedings|publisher= [[Bar-Ilan University]], [[American Mathematical Society]], [[Oxford University Press]] |year= 1999|isbn= 978-0-19-851045-1|oclc= 223099225}}</ref>\n| Provided the first general definitions of a [[commutative ring]], and suggested that topology be studied algebraically.{{Sfn | Dick | 1981|p= 174}} Combined the structure theory of [[associative algebra]]s and the representation theory of groups into a single arithmetic theory of [[module (mathematics)|modules]] and [[ideal (ring theory)|ideals]] in [[ring (mathematics)|rings]] satisfying [[ascending chain condition]]s.<ref name=\"vdWaerden_1985\" >{{harvnb|van der Waerden|1985|p = 244}}.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Non-Euclidean geometry]]'''\n| [[J\u00e1nos Bolyai]],<br />[[Nikolai Lobachevsky]]<ref>[[Marvin Jay Greenberg]], Euclidean and Non-Euclidean geometries: Development and history New York: W. H. Freeman, 1993.</ref>(founders)\n|Independent development of [[hyperbolic geometry]] in which Euclid's fifth postulate is not true\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Number theory]]'''\n| [[Pythagoras]]<ref>p. 46, ''Aristarchus of Samos: The Ancient Copernicus'', Thomas Heath, Oxford, 1913.</ref>\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Probability]]'''\n| [[Gerolamo Cardano]], [[Pierre de Fermat]], [[Blaise Pascal]], [[Christiaan Huygens]]<ref>Stigler, Stephen M. (1990). The History of Statistics: The Measurement of Uncertainty before 1900. Belknap Press/Harvard University Press.</ref> (founders)\n|Fermat and Pascal co-founded [[probability theory]], about which Huygens wrote the first book\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Projective geometry]]'''\n| [[Girard Desargues]]<ref>O'Connor, John J; Edmund F. Robertson \"G\u00e9rard Desargues\". MacTutor History of Mathematics archive.</ref>(founder)\n| By generalizing the use of vanishing points to include the case when these are infinitely far away\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Tensor calculus]]'''\n| [[Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro]]<ref>O'Connor, John J; Edmund F. Robertson \"Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro\". MacTutor History of Mathematics archive.</ref><br />(founder)\n|Book: The Absolute Differential Calculus\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Trigonometry]]'''\n| [[Hipparchus]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Boyer |authorlink=Carl Benjamin Boyer |title=A History of Mathematics |edition=Second |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc. |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-471-54397-8 |chapter=Greek Trigonometry and Mensuration |pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofmathema00boye/page/162 162] |quote=For some two and a half centuries, from Hippocrates to Eratosthenes, Greek mathematicians had studied relationships between lines and circles and had applied these in a variety of astronomical problems, but no systematic trigonometry had resulted. Then, presumably during the second half of the second century B.C., the first trigonometric table apparently was compiled by the astronomer Hipparchus of Nicaea (ca. 180-ca. 125 B.C.), who thus earned the right to be known as ''the father of trigonometry.'' Aristarchus had known that in a given circle the ratio of arc to chord decreases from 180\u00b0 to 0\u00b0, tending toward a limit of 1. However, it appears that not until Hipparchus undertook the task had anyone tabulated corresponding values of arc and chord for a whole series of angles. |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofmathema00boye/page/162 }}</ref><ref>Boyer's opinion may constructively be compared to [[\u00d8ystein Ore]]'s opinion, that the Babylonians constructed trigonometric tables ''ca'' 1600 BCE ({{cite book|last=Ore|title=Number Theory and its History|publisher=Dover Publications, Inc.|year=1988|chapter=Diophantine Problems|pages=[https://archive.org/details/numbertheoryitsh0000orey/page/176 176\u2013179]|isbn=978-0-486-65620-5|quote=The tablet, catalogued as [[Plimpton 322]], is composed in Old Babylonian script so that it must fall in the period from 1900 B.C. and 1600 B.C., at least a millennium before the Pythagoreans\u2026 It is evident, however, that at this early date the Babylonians not only had completely mastered the Pythagorean problem, but also had used it as the basis for the construction of trigonometric tables.|url=https://archive.org/details/numbertheoryitsh0000orey/page/176}})</ref>\n| Constructed the first trigonometric table.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''Vector algebra,'''<br />'''[[vector calculus]]'''\n| [[Josiah Willard Gibbs|Willard Gibbs]]<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">Wheeler, Lynde, Phelps (1951). Josiah Willard Gibbs - the History of a Great Mind. Ox Bow Press.</ref><br />[[Oliver Heaviside]]<ref>Michael J. Crowe (1994). [[A History of Vector Analysis]] : The Evolution of the Idea of a Vectorial System. Dover Publications; Reprint edition.</ref><br />(founders)\n|For their development and use of [[Vector (geometric)|vectors]] in [[algebra]] and [[calculus]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|}\n\n===Systems theory===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Chaos theory]]'''\n| [[Henri Poincar\u00e9]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Chaos Theory and Fractals|url=http://www.tnellen.com/alt/chaos.html|publisher=Mendelson Productions in collaboration with Blumenthal Enterprises|access-date=4 July 2012|author1=Jonathan Mendelson  |author2=Elana Blumenthal |lastauthoramp=yes|quote=Henri Poincar\u00e9 was really the \"Father of Chaos [Theory],\" however.}}</ref><br>[[Mary Cartwright]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cwp.library.ucla.edu/articles/ebcart11.html|title=Mistress of Girton whose mathematical work formed the basis of chaos theory|work=Obituaries Electronic Telegraph|date=11 April 1998|access-date=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>[[Freeman Dyson|Freeman J. Dyson]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=CQeKFG01s-oC&pg=PA169 ''Mary Lucy Cartwright (1900\u20131998): Chaos theory''], pp. 169\u2013177, in ''Out of the Shadows: Contributions of Twentieth-Century Women to Physics'', edited by [[Nina Byers]] and Gary Williams, 498 p. (Cambridge University Press, 2006); {{isbn|0-521-82197-5}}</ref><br />[[Edward Lorenz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2008/obit-lorenz-0416.html|title=Edward Lorenz, father of chaos theory and butterfly effect, dies at 90|website=MIT.edu|access-date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n| Poincar\u00e9's work on the [[three-body problem]] was the first discovered example of a chaotic dynamical system. Cartwright made the first mathematical analysis of dynamical systems with [[chaos theory|chaos]]. Lorenz introduced [[strange attractor]] notation.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Cybernetics]]'''\n| [[Norbert Wiener]]<ref>Conway, F., and Siegelman, J., 2005. ''Dark Hero of the Information Age: in search of Norbert Wiener, the father of cybernetics''. Basic Books, New York. 423pp. {{ISBN|0-7382-0368-8}}</ref>\n| Book ''Cybernetics: Or the Control and Communication in the Animal and the Machine''. 1948.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Dynamic programming]]'''\n| [[Richard E. Bellman]]\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Fuzzy logic]]'''\n| [[Lotfi Asker Zadeh]]\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Information theory]]'''\n| [[Claude Shannon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bell-labs.com/news/2006/october/shannon.html|title=Bell Labs website: \"For example, Claude Shannon, the father of Information Theory, had a passion\u2026\"|website=Bell-Labs.com|access-date=15 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605073153/http://www.bell-labs.com/news/2006/october/shannon.html|archive-date=5 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| Article: ''A Mathematical Theory of Communication'' (1948)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Optimal control]]'''\n| [[Arthur E. Bryson]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aere.iastate.edu/who-we-are/distinguished-alumni/2004-alumni.html|title=2004 Distinguished Alumni<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=IaState.edu|access-date=15 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725203556/http://www.aere.iastate.edu/who-we-are/distinguished-alumni/2004-alumni.html|archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| Book: Applied Optimal Control<ref name=\"Bryson1975\">{{cite book\n| author=Bryson, A.E.\n|author2=Ho, Y.C.\n| year=1975\n| title=Applied optimal control\n| publisher=Washington, DC: Hemisphere\n| isbn=\n}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Robust control]]'''\n| [[George Zames]]{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}}\n| Small gain theorem and [[H infinity]] control.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| ''