ory of international law, war and [[human rights]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Linguistics]]''' (early)\n| [[P\u0101\u1e47ini|Panini]]\n| Wrote the first descriptive grammar (of Sanskrit)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Linguistics]]''' (modern)\n| [[Ferdinand de Saussure]]\n[[Noam Chomsky]]\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Sociology]]'''\n| [[Ibn Khaldun]]<ref name=\"Mowlana\"/><ref name=\"Akhtar\">{{cite journal |author= Akhtar S. W. |year=1997 |title=The Islamic Concept of Knowledge |url= |journal=Al-Tawhid: A Quarterly Journal of Islamic Thought & Culture |volume=12 |issue= |page=3}}</ref><br />[[Adam Ferguson]]<ref>{{cite book |first=William Bradford |last=Willcox |author2=Arnstein, Walter L. |edition=Sixth Edition, 1992 |title=The Age of Aristocracy, 1688 to 1830 |others=Volume III of A History of England, edited by Lacey Baldwin Smith |page=133 |location=[[Lexington, MA]] |year=1966 |isbn=978-0-669-24459-5| quote=Adam Ferguson of Edinburgh became \"the father of modern sociology.\"}}</ref><br />[[Auguste Comte]] (who also coined the term)<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/ebi/article-9273765 Auguste Comte], Britannica Student Encyclopedia. Accessed October 5, 2006.</ref><br />[[Marquis de Condorcet]] (founder)<ref>p. 87, ''Full Meridian of Glory'', Paul Murdin, New York: Springer, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-387-75533-5}} (print), {{ISBN|978-0-387-75534-2}} (online).</ref>\n| Wrote the first sociological book, the ''[[Muqaddimah]]'' (''Prolegomena'').<br />\"Father of modern sociology\"<br />Introduced the [[scientific method]] into sociology.\n|}\n\n===Economics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person(s)<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Accounting]] and [[bookkeeping]] '''\n| [[Luca Pacioli]]<ref name=jkdiwan>{{cite book|last=DIWAN|first=Jaswith|title=ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS & THEORIES|publisher=MORRE|location=LONDON|id=id# 94452|pages=001\u2013002}}</ref>\n| Establisher of accounting and the first person to publish a work on bookkeeping.<ref name=\"jkdiwan\"/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Economics]] (early)'''\n| [[Ibn Khaldun]]<ref>I. M. Oweiss (1988), \"Ibn Khaldun, the Father of Economics\", ''Arab Civilization: Challenges and Responses'', [[New York University Press]], {{ISBN|0-88706-698-4}}.</ref><br />[[Chanakya]] / [[Kautilya]]<ref>L. K. Jha, K. N. Jha (1998). \"Chanakya: the pioneer economist of the world\", International Journal of Social Economics 25 (2-4), p. 267-282</ref>\n|Publication: ''[[Muqaddimah]]'' (1370)<br />Publication: ''[[Arthashastra]]'' (400 BCE - 200 CE)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Economics]] (modern)'''\n| {{unbulleted list\n  |[[Richard Cantillon]]<ref>{{cite book |first=Murray N. |last=Rothbard |authorlink=Murray Rothbard |title=Economic thought before Adam Smith: An Austrian Perspective on the History of Economic Thought |publisher=Edward Elgar |location=Cheltnam, UK |year=2006 |chapter=Chapter 12 \u2014 The founding father of modern economics: Richard Cantillon |pages=345 |isbn=978-0-945466-48-2 |quote=The honour of being called the 'father of modern economics' belongs, then, not to its usual recipient, Adam Smith, but to a gallicized Irish merchant, banker, and adventurer who wrote the first treatise on economics more than four decades before the publication of the ''Wealth of Nations''. Richard Cantillon (c. early 1680s-1734)\u2026|title-link=An Austrian Perspective on the History of Economic Thought }}</ref>\n  |[[Anders Chydenius]]<ref name=\"pelo\">{{cite web |last=Pelo |first=June |title=Anders Chydenius |accessdate=2007-11-26 |url=http://sydaby.eget.net/swe/jp_chydenius.htm}}</ref>\n  |[[Adam Smith]]<ref>Steven Pressman, ''Fifty Major Economists'', Routledge 1999 ({{ISBN|0-415-13481-1}}), p.&nbsp;20.</ref>\n }}\n| {{unbulleted list\n  |First specific treatise on economics.\n  |''[[The National Gain]]'' (1765), a pamphlet that included key ideas about free trade.<ref name=\"acton\">{{cite web |title=Acton Institute: Anders Chydenius (1729-1803) |accessdate=2007-11-26 |url=http://www.acton.org/publications/randl/rl_liberal_en_563.php}}</ref>\n  |''[[The Wealth of Nations]]'' (1776).\n }}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''{{hlist|style=line-height:1.4em; |[[Evolutionary economics]] |[[Ecological economics]] |[[Thermoeconomics]] |[[Bioeconomics (biophysical)|bioeconomics]]}}'''\n| [[Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen]]<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Cleveland C. |author2=Ruth M. |year=1997 |title=When, where, and by how much do biophysical limits constrain the economic process? A survey of Georgescu-Roegen's contribution to ecological economics |url= |journal=Ecological Economics |volume=22 |issue= 3|pages=203\u2013223 |doi=10.1016/s0921-8009(97)00079-7|title-link=biophysical }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Daly H |year=1995 |title=On Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen's contributions to economics: An obituary essay |url= |journal=Ecological Economics |volume=13 |issue= 3|pages=149\u201354 |doi=10.1016/0921-8009(95)00011-w}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Mayumi K |year=1995 |title=Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen (1906-1994) |url= |journal=Structural Change and Economic Dynamics |volume=6 |issue= 3|pages=115\u2013120 |doi=10.1016/0954-349x(95)00014-e}}</ref><ref name=\"MAYUMIGOWDY1999\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Mayumi |editor1-first=Kozo |editor1-link=Kozo Mayumi |editor2-last=Gowdy |editor2-first=John |title=Bioeconomics and Sustainability: Essays in Honor of Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen |year=1999 |publisher=Cheltenham: Edward Elgar |isbn=978-1-85898-667-8}}</ref><ref name=\"MAYUMI2001\">{{cite book |last=Mayumi |first=Kozo |title=The Origins of Ecological Economics: The Bioeconomics of Georgescu-Roegen |year=2001 |publisher=Routledge, Taylor & Francis Group |isbn=978-0-415-23523-5}}</ref>\n| ''[[Nicholas Georgescu-Roegen#Magnum opus on The Entropy Law and the Economic Process|The Entropy Law and the Economic Process]]'' (1971)\n<!--Not a ref: <ref>A principal contribution to [[economics]] by Georgescu-Roegen was the concept of [[entropy]] from [[thermodynamics]] as well as foundational work that later developed into [[evolutionary economics]]. His work also contributed significantly to the emergence of the fields of [[thermoeconomics]] (or [[biophysical economics]], [[Bioeconomics (biophysical)|bioeconomics]] and [[ecological economics]].</ref>-->\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Macroeconomics]]'''\n| [[John Maynard Keynes]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John Maynard Keynes|url=http://www.investopedia.com/terms/j/john_maynard_keynes.asp|website=Investopedia|publisher=Investopedia|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n| Author of ''[[The General Theory of Employment, Interest and Money]]'' and groundbreaking economist, Keynes spearheaded a revolution in economic thinking. Prior to Keynes, the general consensus among economists was that the economy was self-fixing. During the Great Depression, when people began to realize that the economy would not fix itself, Keynes proposed that the government needed to intervene to combat excessive [[boom and bust]]. This idea was the largest influence in U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s [[New Deal]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blinder|first1=Alan|title=Keynesian Economics|url=http://www.econlib.org/library/Enc/KeynesianEconomics.html|website=Library of Economics and Liberty|publisher=Liberty Fund|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Briggs|first1=Brad|title=John Maynard Keynes: The Man Who Transformed the Economic World|url=http://www.investinganswers.com/education/economics/john-maynard-keynes-man-who-transformed-economic-world-621|website=Investing Answers|accessdate=11 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221090737/http://www.investinganswers.com/education/economics/john-maynard-keynes-man-who-transformed-economic-world-621|archive-date=21 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Mathematical economics]]'''\n| [[Daniel Bernoulli]]\n| Forerunner of the ''[[Tableau \u00e9conomique]]''.<ref>Rothbard, p&nbsp;379.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Monetary economics]]'''\n| {{unbulleted list\n  |[[Nicole Oresme]] (c. 1322\u20131382)<ref>Woods, p.&nbsp;155.</ref>\n  |[[Irving Fisher]] (1867\u20131947)\n  |[[Milton Friedman]] (1912\u20132006)\n }}\n| {{unbulleted list\n  |Oresme's ''[[De Moneta]]''.\n  |\"Irving Fisher [...] spent his career studying questions about money and the economy - how money affects interest rates, how money affects inflation, and the impact of money on overall economic activity. For this work, he is regarded as the father of monetary economics.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Pressman |first=Steven |authorlink=Steven Pressman (economist) |title=50 Major Economists |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3H11Xu1F_MkC |accessdate=2013-01-05 |edition=2 |series=Routledge Key Guides |year=2006 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=9780415366489 |page=137}}</ref>\n  |\"[...] no less an authority than the University of Chicago's Milton Friedman, the father of monetary economics, [...]\"<ref>{{cite journal |year=1969 |journal=Dun's Review |volume=94 |pages=146 |accessdate=2013-01-05 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v8cSAQAAMAAJ | title=Dun's Review}}</ref>\n }}\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Microcredit]]'''\n| [[Muhammad Yunus]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.grameen-info.org/dialogue/Dialogue60/indiaFocus.htm |title=\"Expanding Microcredit in India: A Great Opportunity for Poverty Alleviation\", ''Grameen Dialogue''. |access-date=2009-08-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208173029/http://www.grameen-info.org/dialogue/Dialogue60/indiaFocus.htm |archive-date=2012-02-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| Founded [[Grameen Bank]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Personnel economics]]'''\n| [[Edward Lazear]]\n| Published the first paper in the field.\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Family and consumer science]]'''\n| [[Ellen Swallow Richards]]\n| Founded the American Association of Home Economics, currently the American Association of Family & Consumer Sciences. \"Bringing science into the home, Richards hoped to \"...attain the best physical, mental, and moral development\" for the family, which she believed was the basic unit of civilization.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu/alumni/ellen-swallow-richards.html|title=Ellen Swallow Richards - Vassar College Encyclopedia - Vassar College|website=VCEncyclopedia.Vassar.edu|access-date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Schools of thought====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person(s)<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Austrian School]]'''\n| [[Carl Menger]]<ref>Rothbard, p 167</ref>\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[School of Salamanca]]'''\n| [[Francisco de Vitoria]]<ref>Rothbard, p 102</ref>\n| Highly influential teacher and lecturer on [[Business ethics|commercial morality]]\n|}\n\n====Theories====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person(s)<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''Expectations theory'''\n| [[Thomas Cajetan|Thomas Cardinal Cajetan]]<ref>Rothbard, p 100-101</ref>\n| Recognised the effect of market [[Expectation (epistemic)|expectation]]s on the value of [[money]]\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Modern portfolio theory]]'''\n| [[Harry Markowitz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-1662610/Harry-Markowitz-the-father-of.html|title=Find Local Contractors - Home Remodeling Contractors on Ecnext|website=goliath.Ecnext.com|access-date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Social choice theory]]'''\n| [[Kenneth Arrow]]\n| Created the field with his 1951 book ''[[Social Choice and Individual Values]]''.\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Founders of statistics]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:People considered father or mother of a scientific field}}\n[[Category:Lists of scientists|*list]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by name feature|Field]]\n[[Category:Science pioneers| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThe following is a '''list of people who are considered''' a \"'''father'''\" '''or''' \"'''mother'''\" (or \"founding father\" or \"founding mother\") '''of a [[Branches of science|scientific field]]'''. Such people are generally regarded to have made the first significant contributions to and/or delineation of that field; they may also be seen as \"''a''\" rather than \"''the''\" father or mother of the field. Debate over who merits the title can be perennial.\n\n== Science as a whole==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|'''[[Science]] (modern)'''\n| [[Galileo Galilei]] (1564-1642)<ref>Pamela Gossin, ''Encyclopedia of Literature and Science'', 2002.</ref><br /><ref>Finocchiaro, Maurice A. (Fall 2007), \"Book Review\u2014The Person of the Millennium: The Unique Impact of Galileo on World History\", The Historian 69 (3): 601\u2013602</ref><ref>Weidhorn, Manfred (2005). ''The Person of the Millennium: The Unique Impact of Galileo on World History''. Universe, p. 155.</ref>\n| For systemic use of experimentation in [[science]] and contributions to [[scientific method]], [[physics]] and [[observational astronomy]]\n\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''[[Science]] (ancient)'''\n|[[Thales]] (c. 624/623-c. 548/545 BC)<ref>{{cite book |last=Singer |first=C. |title=A Short History of Science to the 19th century |location= |publisher=Streeter Press |year=2008 |page=35 |isbn=}}<!--(copied from [[Thales]]--></ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Needham |first=C. W. |title=Cerebral Logic: Solving the Problem of Mind and Brain |location= |publisher=Loose Leaf |year=1978 |page=75 |isbn=978-0-398-03754-3}}<!--(copied from [[Thales]]--></ref>\n|Attempted to explain natural phenomena without recourse to [[mythology]]\n\n|-\n|[[Democritus]] (c. 460 - c. 370 BC)\n|[[Atomism|Atomist]]<ref>Pamela Gossin, ''Encyclopedia of Literature and Science'', 2002. <!--(copied from [[Democritus]])--></ref>\n|}\n\n== Natural sciences ==\n=== Biology ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!width=\"25%\"| Field\n!width=\"32%\"| Person/s<br />{{nobold|considered \"father\" or \"mother\"}}\n!width=\"43%\"| Rationale\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| '''[[Bacteriology]]'''\n| [[Robert Koch]] (1843-1910){{\\}}[[Ferdinand Cohn]] (1828-1898)<ref>Drews G (1999). \"Ferdinand Cohn, a Founder of Modern Microbiology\". ASM News 65 (8).</ref>{{\\}}[[Louis Pasteur]] (1822-1895)\n|rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"middle\"| First to produce precise, correct descriptions of [[bacteria]].\n</tr>\n|-\n| [[Antonie van Leeuwenhoek]] (1632-1723)<ref name=fm/>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| '''[[Biogeography]]'''\n| [[Alfred Russel Wallace]] (1823-1913)\n| \"...Often described as the Father of Biogeography, Wallace shows the impact of human activity on the natural world.\"<ref>{{cite book |title = Explorers: Tales of Endurance and Exploration |year = 2010 |publisher = Penguin |isbn = 9780756675110 |author = DK Publishing |page = 272 }}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Biology]]'''{{NoteTag|A name suggested in 1802 by the German naturalist [[Gottfried Reinhold Treviranus]] and introduced as a scientific term later that year by [[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck]].}}\n| [[Aristotle]] (384-322 BC)\n| <!--(Aristotle:)-->\n|- valign=\"top\"\n\n| '''[[Botany]]'''\n| [[Theophrastus]] (c. 371-c. 287 BC)\n| <!--(Theophrastus:)-->\n|-\n|'''[[Cheloniology]]'''\n|[[Archie Carr]] (1909-1987)\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://conserveturtles.org/10693-2/|title=Centennial Tribute to Archie Carr- The Father of Sea Turtle Research & Conservation \u2013 Sea Turtle 